{"title_page": "Marion Coyle", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2015}}\n\n'''Marion Coyle''' (born 1954<ref name=\"trib\">{{cite web | title = Herrema's kidnapper explains motive | author = Eamonn McCann | url = http://www.phoblacht.net/emcc711058g.html | publisher = [[The Sunday Tribune]] | date = 23 October 2005 | accessdate = 2007-04-20}}</ref>) is a former member of the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA).\n\n==Background==\nMarion Coyle was born on July 1954 in [[Derry]], [[County Derry]], [[Northern Ireland]], and lived in the Duncreggan Road, a rather middle-class and fashionable area of Derry.<ref>{{cite book |last= Howard |first= Paul |title= Hostage:Notorious Irish Kidnappings |publisher= The O'Brien Press Ltd.  |isbn= 0-86278-769-6}}</ref> Coyle was a student in typing and advanced English at the time of the civil rights demonstrations and civil disorder which culminated in the [[Battle of the Bogside]]. In his work, ''Hostage:Notorious Irish Kidnappings'', Paul Howard notes that Coyle was a very quiet teenager ''\"showing none of the qualities that would make her one of the IRA's most fearless and respected Volunteers''.<ref>Howard p.132</ref> On the night of 26 June 1970 her uncle Joe Coyle, who was a member of the IRA's Derry leadership, along with Thomas Carlin, Tommy McCool and his two young daughters died when a bomb they were preparing in the kitchen of Tommy McCool's house on the Creggan estate exploded prematurely.<ref>Howard p.134</ref> Following this, her brother Phillip was arrested and imprisoned for possession of a firearm. \n\nIn 1973 Coyle and three others were arrested in [[Sligo]] after they were stopped in a car containing guns and ammunition. The alleged IRA Northern OC, Leo Martin was charged in relation to the incident.<ref>Howard p.135</ref> In 1974 Coyle was acquitted of the attempted murder of a Garda officer during the re-arrest of Kevin Mallon in Portlaoise (Mallon had been one of three IRA prisoners airlifted to safety in the [[Mountjoy Prison helicopter escape|1973 Mountjoy Prison helicopter escape]]).\n\n== Monasterevin Siege ==\nOn 3 October 1975 Coyle and another IRA member, Eddie Gallagher, kidnapped industrialist [[Tiede Herrema]] near his home in [[Castletroy]], a suburb of [[Limerick]]. They were traced to a house in [[Monasterevin]], [[County Kildare]], and a two-week siege began. Coyle and Gallagher demanded the release of three republican prisoners, including [[Rose Dugdale]], in return for the release of Herrema, but the authorities refused to grant any concessions. The siege ended on 7 November when Herrema was released, and Coyle and Gallagher were arrested.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | title = 1975: IRA kidnappers release industrialist | author = | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/7/newsid_2539000/2539461.stm | publisher = [[BBC]] | date = 7 November 1975| accessdate = 2007-04-20}}</ref> The kidnapping was the longest in Irish history.<ref>{{cite web | title = IRA kidnap victim gives papers to university | url = http://archives.tcm.ie/breakingnews/2005/10/18/story226030.asp | publisher = BreakingNews.ie | date = 18 October 2005 | accessdate = 2007-04-20 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929104532/http://archives.tcm.ie/breakingnews/2005/10/18/story226030.asp | archivedate = 29 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn March 1976 Coyle was sentenced to 15 years in prison for the abduction, while Gallagher received a 20-year sentence.<ref name=\"bbc\"/> Herrema has stated he believes the sentences were too long, describing Coyle and Gallagher as young people who did something stupid.<ref>{{cite web|title=Herrema recalls 1975 kidnap drama |author=Jimmy Woulfe |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2005/10/19/story213067566.asp |publisher=[[Irish Examiner]] |date=19 October 2005 |accessdate=2007-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071120144708/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2005/10/19/story213067566.asp |archivedate=20 November 2007 }}</ref> Coyle was released from prison in 1985, and Gallagher in 1990.<ref name=\"trib\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{PIRA}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coyle, Marion}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Irish republicans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Derry (city)]]\n[[Category:Provisional Irish Republican Army members]]\n[[Category:Republicans imprisoned during the Northern Ireland conflict]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2015}}\n\n'''Marion Coyle''' (born 1954<ref name=\"trib\">{{cite web | title = Herrema's kidnapper explains motive | author = Eamonn McCann | url = http://www.phoblacht.net/emcc711058g.html | publisher = [[The Sunday Tribune]] | date = 23 October 2005 | accessdate = 2007-04-20}}</ref>) is a former member of the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA).\n\n==Background==\nMarion Coyle was born on July 1954 in [[Derry]], [[County Londonderry]], [[Northern Ireland]], and lived in the Duncreggan Road, a rather middle-class and fashionable area of Derry.<ref>{{cite book |last= Howard |first= Paul |title= Hostage:Notorious Irish Kidnappings |publisher= The O'Brien Press Ltd.  |isbn= 0-86278-769-6}}</ref> Coyle was a student in typing and advanced English at the time of the civil rights demonstrations and civil disorder which culminated in the [[Battle of the Bogside]]. In his work, ''Hostage:Notorious Irish Kidnappings'', Paul Howard notes that Coyle was a very quiet teenager ''\"showing none of the qualities that would make her one of the IRA's most fearless and respected Volunteers''.<ref>Howard p.132</ref> On the night of 26 June 1970 her uncle Joe Coyle, who was a member of the IRA's Derry leadership, along with Thomas Carlin, Tommy McCool and his two young daughters died when a bomb they were preparing in the kitchen of Tommy McCool's house on the Creggan estate exploded prematurely.<ref>Howard p.134</ref> Following this, her brother Phillip was arrested and imprisoned for possession of a firearm. \n\nIn 1973 Coyle and three others were arrested in [[Sligo]] after they were stopped in a car containing guns and ammunition. The alleged IRA Northern OC, Leo Martin was charged in relation to the incident.<ref>Howard p.135</ref> In 1974 Coyle was acquitted of the attempted murder of a Garda officer during the re-arrest of Kevin Mallon in Portlaoise (Mallon had been one of three IRA prisoners airlifted to safety in the [[Mountjoy Prison helicopter escape|1973 Mountjoy Prison helicopter escape]]).\n\n== Monasterevin Siege ==\nOn 3 October 1975 Coyle and another IRA member, Eddie Gallagher, kidnapped industrialist [[Tiede Herrema]] near his home in [[Castletroy]], a suburb of [[Limerick]]. They were traced to a house in [[Monasterevin]], [[County Kildare]], and a two-week siege began. Coyle and Gallagher demanded the release of three republican prisoners, including [[Rose Dugdale]], in return for the release of Herrema, but the authorities refused to grant any concessions. The siege ended on 7 November when Herrema was released, and Coyle and Gallagher were arrested.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | title = 1975: IRA kidnappers release industrialist | author = | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/7/newsid_2539000/2539461.stm | publisher = [[BBC]] | date = 7 November 1975| accessdate = 2007-04-20}}</ref> The kidnapping was the longest in Irish history.<ref>{{cite web | title = IRA kidnap victim gives papers to university | url = http://archives.tcm.ie/breakingnews/2005/10/18/story226030.asp | publisher = BreakingNews.ie | date = 18 October 2005 | accessdate = 2007-04-20 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929104532/http://archives.tcm.ie/breakingnews/2005/10/18/story226030.asp | archivedate = 29 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn March 1976 Coyle was sentenced to 15 years in prison for the abduction, while Gallagher received a 20-year sentence.<ref name=\"bbc\"/> Herrema has stated he believes the sentences were too long, describing Coyle and Gallagher as young people who did something stupid.<ref>{{cite web|title=Herrema recalls 1975 kidnap drama |author=Jimmy Woulfe |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2005/10/19/story213067566.asp |publisher=[[Irish Examiner]] |date=19 October 2005 |accessdate=2007-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071120144708/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2005/10/19/story213067566.asp |archivedate=20 November 2007 }}</ref> Coyle was released from prison in 1985, and Gallagher in 1990.<ref name=\"trib\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{PIRA}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coyle, Marion}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Irish republicans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Derry (city)]]\n[[Category:Provisional Irish Republican Army members]]\n[[Category:Republicans imprisoned during the Northern Ireland conflict]]\n", "name_user": "193.120.236.35", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBackground)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marion_Coyle"}
